  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Cognitive load is the total amount of mental effort being used in working memory. John Sweller\u0026rsquo;s cognitive load theory distinguishes three types: intrinsic load (the complexity inherent to the material), extraneous load (effort caused by poor instructional design), and germane load (effort devoted to building understanding) [@sweller1988].\nWorking memory is limited — it can hold roughly four to seven elements at a time. When a lesson, document, or specification overloads working memory through dense vocabulary, tangled syntax, or too many simultaneous concepts, comprehension drops regardless of how correct the content is.\n",
